</footer>



    <section class="po-hr-cn prt-y">

      <h1 class="po-hr-cn__title">How to Build a Socialist Foreign Policy</h1>

      <div class="po-hr-cn__contributors">
        <dl class="po-hr-cn__authors">
          
            
            
              <dt class="po-hr-cn__byline">By</dt>
            
          
          
            <dd class="po-hr-cn__author">
              <a class="po-hr-cn__author-link" href="/author/richard-lachmann">Richard Lachmann</a>
            </dd>
          
        </dl>
        
          
        
      </div>

      <p class="po-hr-cn__dek">Our hopes for a socialist United States are constrained as much by US empire as they are by domestic capitalists. But democratic socialist candidates like Bernie Sanders can combat militarism in the service of workers across the world.</p>
    </section>

    

    
      
        <figure class="po-hr-im prt-x">
          
            
            

            <img alt class="po-hr-im__image" height="769" src="https://images.jacobinmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/12154637/GettyImages-1094224234.jpg" width="1024"/>

            
              
                <figcaption class="po-hr-im__caption">
                  <p class="po-hr-im__description">Sen. Bernie Sanders (I-VT) looks at his notes as he watches the State of the Union address in the chamber of the U.S. House of Representatives at the U.S. Capitol Building on February 5, 2019 in Washington, DC. Win McNamee / Getty Images</p>
                </figcaption>
              
            
          
        </figure>

      
    

</header>


        

